I"I<h2 id="sensors">Sensors</h2>

<p>Sensors is a command-line utility to monitor CPU and GPU temperature in Linux. It is a free and open-source tool. It helps you to see the readings of all sensor chips including the CPU. You can also monitor fans of your system with this tool..Run the following command in Ubuntu to install Sensors.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">sudo </span>apt-get <span class="nb">install </span>lm-sensors
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Run the following command to detect all the available sensors on your system.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">sudo </span>sensors-detect
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>After detecting the available sensors on your system, run the following command to monitor CPU and GPU temperature.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sensors
</code></pre></div></div>

<h2 id="glances">Glances</h2>

<p>Glances is a cross-platform real-time system monitoring tool. You access it via a web browser to remotely monitor your Linux server. It is a curses-based system monitoring tool written in Python</p>

<p>Run the following command install Glances on your system:</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>curl <span class="nt">-L</span> https://bit.ly/glances | /bin/bash
OR
wget <span class="nt">-O-</span> https://bit.ly/glances | /bin/bash
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Once you have installed it, start Glances with the following command and press f key to view sensors information.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>glances
</code></pre></div></div>
